but the second question relates to page

43:44.070 --> 43:47.570
item three four, where you have your performance

43:47.730 --> 43:52.118
measures and you don't have any targets for

43:52.284 --> 43:55.958
first call response for either fire or EMS in 2023.

43:55.964 --> 43:58.780
And then on that same page,

43:59.630 --> 44:03.610
you talk about EMS incidents and responses and

44:03.760 --> 44:07.306
fire incidents and responses, and responses are

44:07.408 --> 44:11.306
a lot higher than the incidents. And I'm just wondering what's

44:11.338 --> 44:14.686
the difference between those two. So the reason for

44:14.708 --> 44:18.474
that, Doug, is we're switching to accreditation measures.

44:18.522 --> 44:21.230
In the past, we were reporting averages.

44:21.810 --> 44:25.246
The average means that half the time you're better, but half the time you're

44:25.278 --> 44:29.282
worse. The accreditation measure now is based

44:29.336 --> 44:32.398
on percentiles. The 90th percentile is what they're

44:32.414 --> 44:36.642
measuring. That gives a better picture

44:36.706 --> 44:40.246
of your capacity and the type

44:40.268 --> 44:43.400
of service you're delivering. That's the reason for that change.

44:43.930 --> 44:47.000
We're also looking at outcome based

44:47.470 --> 44:51.974
responses instead of just simply showing

44:52.022 --> 44:55.434
up in a certain amount

44:55.472 --> 44:58.986
of time and stopping the clock. Again, that's the

44:59.008 --> 45:03.166
reason right now that you're seeing a lot of first

45:03.348 --> 45:06.442
response units, ladder trucks, fire trucks,

45:06.506 --> 45:09.550
when you actually need a medical and EMS transport unit.

45:10.690 --> 45:14.390
We haven't been tracking that appropriately. We're stopping

45:14.410 --> 45:18.210
the clock based on response times without really looking at the outcome.

45:18.710 --> 45:22.542
That is going to provide me the analysis and the tools

45:22.686 --> 45:26.178
to make the case for those additional units that

45:26.344 --> 45:29.586
we desperately need. I know we need more ambulances.

45:29.698 --> 45:33.222
That's the reason that we're sending the first available unit. A lot of times

45:33.356 --> 45:36.706
they show up just to stop the clock and then they're

45:36.738 --> 45:40.330
waiting for that ambulance and transport unit to arrive minutes

45:40.400 --> 45:43.914
later. The answer to that is not

45:44.112 --> 45:47.574
adding more fire trucks. It's adding more ambulance capacity,

45:47.622 --> 45:51.454
which will help the system. It'll improve the response times for

45:51.492 --> 45:55.422
transport and it really will improve the working

45:55.476 --> 45:59.614
environment. Thank you, Chief. And what

45:59.652 --> 46:03.200
about the incidents and response difference between those two?

46:04.050 --> 46:05.440
What are you looking at?

